ent; and 4) beryllium fluoride induced maximal I$_{\textrm{H}}$ even in the absence of nucleotide. These data indicate that I$_{\textrm{H}}$ occurs when NKA is in an externally open E2P state with nucleotide bound, a conformation that can be reached through forward Na/K pump phosphorylation of E1, with Na$^{\textrm{+}}$$_{\textrm{i}}$ and ATP, or by backward binding of K$^{\textrm{+}}$$_{\textrm{i}}$ to E1, which drives the pump to the occluded E2(2K), where free P$_{\textrm{i}}$ (at the micromolar levels found in millimolar ATP solutions) promotes external release of occluded K$^{\textrm{+}}$ by backdoor NKA phosphorylation. Maximal I$_{\textrm{H}}$ through beryllium-fluorinated NKA indicates that this complex mimics ATP-bound E2P states.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}},
